Hey there! I'm putting together a little coding challenge for the trivia segment of my next themed dinner party — it's a “Tech Meets Art” night, and I want to throw in a quick data-structures puzzle. 

I have this Python function that's supposed to delete a node from a binary search tree, but I think it's missing a few edge-case details. Here's what I've got so far:

```python
class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, x):
        self.val = x
        self.left = None
        self.right = None

def deleteNode(root, key):
    if root is None:
        return None

    if key < root.val:
        root.left = deleteNode(root.left, key)
    elif key > root.val:
        root.right = deleteNode(root.right, key)
    else:
        if root.left is None:
            root = root.right
        elif root.right is None:
            root = root.left
        else:
            temp_val = minValueNode(root.right).val
            root.val = temp_val
            root.right = deleteNode(root.right, temp_val)

    return root
```

Could you give me a corrected version that properly handles all three cases (no children, one child, two children) and includes any helper functions it needs? A brief explanation of what was wrong and why your fix works would be great too — I'll copy-paste it into the party handout. Thanks!

